05453nam a22007935i 9781442684980DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426849807 a10.3138/97814426849802doi  a(DE-B1597)626543  a(OCoLC)1322125697  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ1236.5.C2bS49 2007 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a342.710291 aSharpe, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Persons Case :bThe Origins and Legacy of the Fight for Legal Personhood /cPatricia I. McMahon, Robert J. Sharpe. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOsgoode Society for Canadian Legal History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword: The Osgoode Society For Canadian Legal History -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: ‘A Relic of Days More Barbarous Than Ours’ -- t1 First of the Five -- t2 The Other Four -- t3 Women and the Law: The Trials of Legal Personhood -- t4 Emily Murphy’s Senate Campaign -- t5 Going to Court -- t6 The Supreme Court of Canada -- t7 The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council and the Canadian Constitution -- t8 Waiting to Be Heard -- t9 The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council Decides -- t10 The Political, Cultural, and Legal Legacy of the Persons -- tNotes -- tArchival Sources -- tFacsimile of the Amended Petition – November 1927 -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex -- tPublications of the Osgoode Society for Canadian Legal History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn 18 October 1929, John Sankey, England's reform-minded Lord Chancellor, ruled in the Persons case that women were eligible for appointment to Canada's Senate. Initiated by Edmonton judge Emily Murphy and four other activist women, the Persons case challenged the exclusion of women from Canada's upper house and the idea that the meaning of the constitution could not change with time. The Persons Case considers the case in its political and social context and examines the lives of the key players: Emily Murphy, Nellie McClung, and the other members of the "famous five," the politicians who opposed the appointment of women, the lawyers who argued the case, and the judges who decided it. Robert J. Sharpe and Patricia I. McMahon examine the Persons case as a pivotal moment in the struggle for women's rights and as one of the most important constitutional decisions in Canadian history. Lord Sankey's decision overruled the Supreme Court of Canada's judgment that the courts could not depart from the original intent of the framers of Canada's constitution in 1867. Describing the constitution as a "living tree," the decision led to a reassessment of the nature of the constitution itself. After the Persons case, it could no longer be viewed as fixed and unalterable, but had to be treated as a document that, in the words of Sankey, was in "a continuous process of evolution." The Persons Case is a comprehensive study of this important event, examining the case itself, the ruling of the Privy Council, and the profound affect that it had on women's rights and the constitutional history of Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPersons (Law)zCanadaxHistory. 0aPolitical rightszCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etczCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen's rightszCanadaxHistory. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh1 aMcMahon, Patricia I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcMurtry, R. Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08